#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:5
msgid "Three ways to wrap - getting started"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:7
msgid ""
"Wrapping Fortran or C functions to Python using F2PY consists of the "
"following steps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:10
msgid ""
"Creating the so-called :doc:`signature file <signature-file>` that contains "
"descriptions of wrappers to Fortran or C functions, also called the "
"signatures of the functions. For Fortran routines, F2PY can create an "
"initial signature file by scanning Fortran source codes and tracking all "
"relevant information needed to create wrapper functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:16
msgid ""
"Optionally, F2PY-created signature files can be edited to optimize wrapper "
"functions, which can make them \"smarter\" and more \"Pythonic\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:19
msgid ""
"F2PY reads a signature file and writes a Python C/API module containing "
"Fortran/C/Python bindings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:22
msgid ""
"F2PY compiles all sources and builds an extension module containing the "
"wrappers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:25
msgid ""
"In building the extension modules, F2PY uses ``meson`` and used to use "
"``numpy.distutils`` For different build systems, see :ref:`f2py-bldsys`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:31
msgid "See :ref:`f2py-meson-distutils` for migration information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:34
msgid ""
"Depending on your operating system, you may need to install the Python "
"development headers (which provide the file ``Python.h``) separately. In "
"Linux Debian-based distributions this package should be called ``python3-"
"dev``, in Fedora-based distributions it is ``python3-devel``. For macOS, "
"depending how Python was installed, your mileage may vary. In Windows, the "
"headers are typically installed already, see :ref:`f2py-windows`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:43
msgid ""
"F2PY supports all the operating systems SciPy is tested on so their `system "
"dependencies panel`_ is a good reference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:46
msgid ""
"Depending on the situation, these steps can be carried out in a single "
"composite command or step-by-step; in which case some steps can be omitted "
"or combined with others."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:50
msgid ""
"Below, we describe three typical approaches of using F2PY with Fortran 77. "
"These can be read in order of increasing effort, but also cater to different "
"access levels depending on whether the Fortran code can be freely modified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:54
msgid ""
"The following example Fortran 77 code will be used for illustration, save it "
"as ``fib1.f``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:57
msgid ""
"C FILE: FIB1.F\n"
"      SUBROUTINE FIB(A,N)\n"
"C\n"
"C     CALCULATE FIRST N FIBONACCI NUMBERS\n"
"C\n"
"      INTEGER N\n"
"      REAL*8 A(N)\n"
"      DO I=1,N\n"
"         IF (I.EQ.1) THEN\n"
"            A(I) = 0.0D0\n"
"         ELSEIF (I.EQ.2) THEN\n"
"            A(I) = 1.0D0\n"
"         ELSE \n"
"            A(I) = A(I-1) + A(I-2)\n"
"         ENDIF\n"
"      ENDDO\n"
"      END\n"
"C END FILE FIB1.F\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:62
msgid ""
"F2PY parses Fortran/C signatures to build wrapper functions to be used with "
"Python. However, it is not a compiler, and does not check for additional "
"errors in source code, nor does it implement the entire language standards. "
"Some errors may pass silently (or as warnings) and need to be verified by "
"the user."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:69
msgid "The quick way"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:71
msgid ""
"The quickest way to wrap the Fortran subroutine ``FIB`` for use in Python is "
"to run"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:76
msgid "python -m numpy.f2py -c fib1.f -m fib1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:78
msgid "or, alternatively, if the ``f2py`` command-line tool is available,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:82
msgid "f2py -c fib1.f -m fib1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:86
msgid ""
"Because the ``f2py`` command might not be available in all system, notably "
"on Windows, we will use the ``python -m numpy.f2py`` command throughout this "
"guide."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:90
msgid ""
"This command compiles and wraps ``fib1.f`` (``-c``) to create the extension "
"module ``fib1.so`` (``-m``) in the current directory. A list of command line "
"options can be seen by executing ``python -m numpy.f2py``.  Now, in Python "
"the Fortran subroutine ``FIB`` is accessible via ``fib1.fib``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:95
msgid ""
">>> import numpy as np\n"
">>> import fib1\n"
">>> print(fib1.fib.__doc__)\n"
"fib(a,[n])\n"
"\n"
"Wrapper for ``fib``.\n"
"\n"
"Parameters\n"
"----------\n"
"a : input rank-1 array('d') with bounds (n)\n"
"\n"
"Other parameters\n"
"----------------\n"
"n : input int, optional\n"
"    Default: len(a)\n"
"\n"
">>> a = np.zeros(8, 'd')\n"
">>> fib1.fib(a)\n"
">>> print(a)\n"
"[  0.   1.   1.   2.   3.   5.   8.  13.]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:118
msgid ""
"Note that F2PY recognized that the second argument ``n`` is the dimension of "
"the first array argument ``a``. Since by default all arguments are input-"
"only arguments, F2PY concludes that ``n`` can be optional with the default "
"value ``len(a)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:123
msgid "One can use different values for optional ``n``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:125
msgid ""
">>> a1 = np.zeros(8, 'd')\n"
">>> fib1.fib(a1, 6)\n"
">>> print(a1)\n"
"[ 0.  1.  1.  2.  3.  5.  0.  0.]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:130
msgid ""
"but an exception is raised when it is incompatible with the input array "
"``a``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:133
msgid ""
">>> fib1.fib(a, 10)\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"  File \"<stdin>\", line 1, in <module>\n"
"fib.error: (len(a)>=n) failed for 1st keyword n: fib:n=10\n"
">>>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:139
msgid ""
"F2PY implements basic compatibility checks between related arguments in "
"order to avoid unexpected crashes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:142
msgid ""
"When a NumPy array that is :term:`Fortran <Fortran order>` :term:"
"`contiguous` and has a ``dtype`` corresponding to a presumed Fortran type is "
"used as an input array argument, then its C pointer is directly passed to "
"Fortran."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:147
msgid ""
"Otherwise, F2PY makes a contiguous copy (with the proper ``dtype``) of the "
"input array and passes a C pointer of the copy to the Fortran subroutine. As "
"a result, any possible changes to the (copy of) input array have no effect "
"on the original argument, as demonstrated below::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:152
msgid ""
">>> a = np.ones(8, 'i')\n"
">>> fib1.fib(a)\n"
">>> print(a)\n"
"[1 1 1 1 1 1 1 1]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:157
msgid ""
"Clearly, this is unexpected, as Fortran typically passes by reference. That "
"the above example worked with ``dtype=float`` is considered accidental."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:160
msgid ""
"F2PY provides an ``intent(inplace)`` attribute that modifies the attributes "
"of an input array so that any changes made by the Fortran routine will be "
"reflected in the input argument. For example, if one specifies the "
"``intent(inplace) a`` directive (see :ref:`f2py-attributes` for details), "
"then the example above would read::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:166
msgid ""
">>> a = np.ones(8, 'i')\n"
">>> fib1.fib(a)\n"
">>> print(a)\n"
"[  0.   1.   1.   2.   3.   5.   8.  13.]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:171
msgid ""
"However, the recommended way to have changes made by Fortran subroutine "
"propagate to Python is to use the ``intent(out)`` attribute. That approach "
"is more efficient and also cleaner."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:175
msgid ""
"The usage of ``fib1.fib`` in Python is very similar to using ``FIB`` in "
"Fortran. However, using *in situ* output arguments in Python is poor style, "
"as there are no safety mechanisms in Python to protect against wrong "
"argument types. When using Fortran or C, compilers discover any type "
"mismatches during the compilation process, but in Python the types must be "
"checked at runtime. Consequently, using *in situ* output arguments in Python "
"may lead to difficult to find bugs, not to mention the fact that the codes "
"will be less readable when all required type checks are implemented."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:184
msgid ""
"Though the approach to wrapping Fortran routines for Python discussed so far "
"is very straightforward, it has several drawbacks (see the comments above). "
"The drawbacks are due to the fact that there is no way for F2PY to determine "
"the actual intention of the arguments; that is, there is ambiguity in "
"distinguishing between input and output arguments. Consequently, F2PY "
"assumes that all arguments are input arguments by default."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:191
msgid ""
"There are ways (see below) to remove this ambiguity by \"teaching\" F2PY "
"about the true intentions of function arguments, and F2PY is then able to "
"generate more explicit, easier to use, and less error prone wrappers for "
"Fortran functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:197
msgid "The smart way"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:199
msgid ""
"If we want to have more control over how F2PY will treat the interface to "
"our Fortran code, we can apply the wrapping steps one by one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:202
msgid "First, we create a signature file from ``fib1.f`` by running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:206
msgid "python -m numpy.f2py fib1.f -m fib2 -h fib1.pyf"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:208
msgid ""
"The signature file is saved to ``fib1.pyf`` (see the ``-h`` flag) and its "
"contents are shown below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:211
msgid ""
"!    -*- f90 -*-\n"
"python module fib2 ! in \n"
"    interface  ! in :fib2\n"
"        subroutine fib(a,n) ! in :fib2:fib1.f\n"
"            real*8 dimension(n) :: a\n"
"            integer optional,check(len(a)>=n),depend(a) :: n=len(a)\n"
"        end subroutine fib\n"
"    end interface \n"
"end python module fib2\n"
"\n"
"! This file was auto-generated with f2py (version:2.28.198-1366).\n"
"! See http://cens.ioc.ee/projects/f2py2e/\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:214
msgid ""
"Next, we'll teach F2PY that the argument ``n`` is an input argument (using "
"the ``intent(in)`` attribute) and that the result, i.e., the contents of "
"``a`` after calling the Fortran function ``FIB``, should be returned to "
"Python (using the ``intent(out)`` attribute). In addition, an array ``a`` "
"should be created dynamically using the size determined by the input "
"argument ``n`` (using the ``depend(n)`` attribute to indicate this "
"dependence relation)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:221
msgid ""
"The contents of a suitably modified version of ``fib1.pyf`` (saved as ``fib2."
"pyf``) are as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:224
msgid ""
"!    -*- f90 -*-\n"
"python module fib2 \n"
"    interface\n"
"        subroutine fib(a,n)\n"
"            real*8 dimension(n),intent(out),depend(n) :: a\n"
"            integer intent(in) :: n\n"
"        end subroutine fib\n"
"    end interface \n"
"end python module fib2\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:227
msgid ""
"Finally, we build the extension module with ``numpy.distutils`` by running:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:231
msgid "python -m numpy.f2py -c fib2.pyf fib1.f"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:233
msgid "In Python::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:235
msgid ""
">>> import fib2\n"
">>> print(fib2.fib.__doc__)\n"
"a = fib(n)\n"
"\n"
"Wrapper for ``fib``.\n"
"\n"
"Parameters\n"
"----------\n"
"n : input int\n"
"\n"
"Returns\n"
"-------\n"
"a : rank-1 array('d') with bounds (n)\n"
"\n"
">>> print(fib2.fib(8))\n"
"[  0.   1.   1.   2.   3.   5.   8.  13.]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:254
msgid ""
"The signature of ``fib2.fib`` now more closely corresponds to the intention "
"of the Fortran subroutine ``FIB``: given the number ``n``, ``fib2.fib`` "
"returns the first ``n`` Fibonacci numbers as a NumPy array. The new Python "
"signature ``fib2.fib`` also rules out the unexpected behaviour in ``fib1."
"fib``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:260
msgid ""
"Note that by default, using a single ``intent(out)`` also implies "
"``intent(hide)``. Arguments that have the ``intent(hide)`` attribute "
"specified will not be listed in the argument list of a wrapper function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:264
msgid "For more details, see :doc:`signature-file`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:267
msgid "The quick and smart way"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:269
msgid ""
"The \"smart way\" of wrapping Fortran functions, as explained above, is "
"suitable for wrapping (e.g. third party) Fortran codes for which "
"modifications to their source codes are not desirable nor even possible."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:274
msgid ""
"However, if editing Fortran codes is acceptable, then the generation of an "
"intermediate signature file can be skipped in most cases. F2PY specific "
"attributes can be inserted directly into Fortran source codes using F2PY "
"directives. A F2PY directive consists of special comment lines (starting "
"with ``Cf2py`` or ``!f2py``, for example) which are ignored by Fortran "
"compilers but interpreted by F2PY as normal lines."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:281
msgid ""
"Consider a modified version of the previous Fortran code with F2PY "
"directives, saved as ``fib3.f``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:284
msgid ""
"C FILE: FIB3.F\n"
"      SUBROUTINE FIB(A,N)\n"
"C\n"
"C     CALCULATE FIRST N FIBONACCI NUMBERS\n"
"C\n"
"      INTEGER N\n"
"      REAL*8 A(N)\n"
"Cf2py intent(in) n\n"
"Cf2py intent(out) a\n"
"Cf2py depend(n) a\n"
"      DO I=1,N\n"
"         IF (I.EQ.1) THEN\n"
"            A(I) = 0.0D0\n"
"         ELSEIF (I.EQ.2) THEN\n"
"            A(I) = 1.0D0\n"
"         ELSE \n"
"            A(I) = A(I-1) + A(I-2)\n"
"         ENDIF\n"
"      ENDDO\n"
"      END\n"
"C END FILE FIB3.F\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:287
msgid "Building the extension module can be now carried out in one command::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:289
msgid "python -m numpy.f2py -c -m fib3 fib3.f"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:291
msgid ""
"Notice that the resulting wrapper to ``FIB`` is as \"smart\" (unambiguous) "
"as in the previous case::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/f2py.getting-started.rst:294
msgid ""
">>> import fib3\n"
">>> print(fib3.fib.__doc__)\n"
"a = fib(n)\n"
"\n"
"Wrapper for ``fib``.\n"
"\n"
"Parameters\n"
"----------\n"
"n : input int\n"
"\n"
"Returns\n"
"-------\n"
"a : rank-1 array('d') with bounds (n)\n"
"\n"
">>> print(fib3.fib(8))\n"
"[  0.   1.   1.   2.   3.   5.   8.  13.]"
msgstr ""
